<Japan1Br>(aUS) <New airbases in the Marianas is an opportunity we couldn't miss. Now that the brand new B-29s "Superfortress" are available in large numbers, we can think about a methodical bombing campaign against Japan, such as the one, which is currently being carried on by the 8th Air Force against Germany. The long-range Mustang should provide an efficient fighter escort to the bombers all their way long to the Home Islands - in addition, fighter sweeps will be conducted in order to silence any Imperial air opposition prior to our bomber strikes. Industrial centres will be our first target - you're assigned to the Kyushu sector, an important industrial, Navy yard and Army command centre. Show the Japanese they can't be in security anywhere as long as they will resist hopelessly our unmatchable air supremacy.>
<Japan1VictoryDb>(aUS) <Congratulations, officer. Japanese losses in the air and on the ground were very heavy thanks to your effective fighter support. Our bombers managed to hit the enemy industry hard, turning Kyushu into a useless burning hell for the Japanese army and economy. Enemy fighters are not taking off anymore, even to defend their own homeland - it a sign that shows how much the enemy Army morale is getting low, thanks to your efforts.>
<Japan1DefeatDb>(aUS) <We didn't think the enemy forces would oppose such a resistance to our bombers. The B-29s proved to be vulnerable to the enemy fighters despite their heavy defensive armament - actually, if our fighters had been a little more efficient at protecting their big friends, our loss rate would perhaps be lower than it is… We have to think about a new strategy - apparently, Japan is not ready to collapse yet!>
<Japan1Db>(aUS) <General Lemay believes that the number will eventually compensate the poor accuracy of our bombardments. Actually, it is true we didn't exactly meet our first objectives during the bombing phase, as the B-29s action was a little disappointing. Fortunately, the fighters did their job well and the enemy fighters suffered much from our airmen aggressive action.>

<Japan1Br>(nUS) <Our carrier force has to clear Kyushu from enemy air activity, prior to our new offensive in the Western Pacific. You will fly offensive missions against the island's airbases, looking for any military target of opportunity the destruction of which would prove valuable for our Command: it includes any kind of airplanes, military convoys, trains, ships, fuel dumps and military installations you may encounter. The destruction of the enemy air and naval assets are the primary target of our massive strikes. Don't forget to provide an efficient fighter cover to our carriers, as never before in this war American warships will have got so close from the Japanese coast.>
<Japan1VictoryDb>(nUS) <Good job, pilot! You did wreak havoc the Japanese airbases. Kyushu is covered by hundreds of useless Japanese aircraft wrecks, while harbours are blocked with capsized hulls of dead Imperial warships - we can now proceed with our planned invasions in the Western theatre with no fear of a massive enemy air resistance.>
<Japan1DefeatDb>(nUS) <Our strikes against Kyushu gave poor results. We shot down many aircrafts, but we failed at clearly challenge the enemy air supremacy over the island. In addition, anchored IJN ships suffered only light damage, if not at all. The price for such little results was high, and our ships had to face heavy and deadly enemy attacks from mainland aircrafts all the time long. The next time we come over there, we will have learnt from this little disappointment.>
<Japan1Db>(nUS) <You did a very good job at harassing the military assets on Kyushu. The enemy air force suffered much too, even if the Japanese managed to withdraw the main bulk of their forces somewhere our aircrafts couldn't reach. Our losses were light, considering how close we were from the Home Islands - this fact has to be taken into account for the day we'll get back there for another round.>

<Japan1Br>(nUK) <Our carrier force has to clear Kyushu from enemy air activity, prior to our new offensive in the Western Pacific. You will fly offensive missions against the island's airbases, looking for any military target of opportunity the destruction of which would prove valuable for our Command: it includes any kind of airplanes, military convoys, trains, ships, fuel dumps and military installations you may encounter. The destruction of the enemy air and naval assets are the primary target of our massive strikes. Don't forget to provide an efficient fighter cover to our carriers, as never before in this war British warships will have got so close from the Japanese coast.>
<Japan1VictoryDb>(nUK) <Good job, pilot! You did wreak havoc the Japanese airbases. Kyushu is covered by hundreds of useless Japanese aircraft wrecks, while harbours are blocked with capsized hulls of dead Imperial warships - we can now proceed with our planned invasions in the Western theatre with no fear of a massive enemy air resistance.>
<Japan1DefeatDb>(nUK) <Our strikes against Kyushu gave poor results. We shot down many aircrafts, but we failed at clearly challenge the enemy air supremacy over the island. In addition, anchored IJN ships suffered only light damage, if not at all. The price for such little results was high, and our ships had to face heavy and deadly enemy attacks from mainland aircrafts all the time long. The next time we come over there, we will have learnt from this little disappointment.>
<Japan1Db>(nUK) <You did a very good job at harassing the military assets on Kyushu. The enemy air force suffered much too, even if the Japanese managed to withdraw the main bulk of their forces somewhere our aircrafts couldn't reach. Our losses were light, considering how close we were from the Home Islands - this fact has to be taken into account for the day we'll get back there for another round.>

<Japan1Br>(*JA) <Sons of the Emperor, for the first time since centuries of warfare, our homeland is threatened by the enemy. Indeed, evil forces managed to put into action several airbases thousands kilometres away, which are now used as vanguard platforms for heavy bomber raids against the Home Islands. In addition, the enemy carrier fleet is believed to prepare direct attacks against our bases in preparation for their next infamous attack against one of our territories. Kyushu, as the southern island of our main archipelago, is the most vulnerable target. You must both protect the southern approach to Honshu and push back any offensive action against Kyushu and its northern city and industrial core. Not a single American plane should escape safely our holy soil and the wrath of our valiant fighters.>
<Japan1VictoryDb>(*JA) <Samurai, you managed to keep our deep sky clean of the western barbarians insult. The B-29 squadrons were severely hit by your uncommon efficiency and your superior tactics. The enemy strategic bombing campaign is a total failure, as it did not manage to stop our industry and break our courageous civilians' morale. More than that, the shy attempts of the US Navy to strike our coastal defences turned into a slaughter for the American crews. The Emperor is proud of you!>
<Japan1DefeatDb>(*JA) <Kyushu is burning, as our fighter squadrons proved unable to hamper the enemy aggression. Tons and tons of bombs fell on our cities, while the unopposed bombers could get back to their base safely. In addition, USAAF and USN fighters depleted our airbases and destroyed hundreds of valuable fighters on the ground, with very few losses on their side. Such a situation will eventually lead us to unusual sacrifices if we want to keep our honour clean and our victory chances intact.>
<Japan1Db>(*JA) <We did suffer much from the enemy bombing campaign, but on the other hand, the enemy B-29s paid a very big tribute to our violent and divine anger. Bombers fell like dead leaves everywhere on Kyushu, as the proof of your deadly efficiency - but if we want to push the bombers back for good, we will have to make even more efforts.>

<SantaCruzBr>(*U*) <Admiral Kinkaid is tasked with the mission of intercepting an enemy carrier force north of Santa Cruz Islands, which is believed to provide air cover to a new huge enemy ressuplying effort. TF.16 and 17 are the only naval air forces available so far, as USS Wasp - please rest in peace - and USS Saratoga were put out of action due to the aggressive enemy submarine activity. As we don't have many clues about the current location of the enemy forces, your airgroups are to make extensive search missions in the area, while Henderson Field planes will seek and destroy the transport force, which will be transiting through the Slot any day now. Try to hit hard the enemy carriers without risking uselessly our own forces.>
<SantaCruzVictoryDb>(*U*) <Admiral Halsey is proud of his boys! Admiral Kinkaid managed to give a severe blow to the enemy Carrier Division, without risking the loss of our own precious carriers. Enemy airgroups were depleted, and the transport force is now left without any serious cover - Cactus Force will turn it into a bunch of burning wrecks if ever they dare to show up. This was certainly the last serious Japanese effort towards Guadalcanal - and the Marines are glad you pushed it back this way!>
<SantaCruzDefeatDb>(*U*) <We failed at hitting severely the enemy fleet. What is even more serious is the complete loss of our carrier forces in the area, which left Henderson Field and the Slot without any air cover. Now, the enemy is free to launch unopposed a heavy resupplying effort - let's hope that our valiant surface groups and Cactus Force will manage to efficiently stop them without our help.>
<SantaCruzDb>(*U*) <Losses were important on both sides, and the carrier forces literally put each other out of action. I don't know if we can talk about any winner or loser here - for a change, the final victory will be a matter of surface action around Guadalcanal.>

<SantaCruzBr>(*JA) <Admiral Yamamoto designed a new trap that should bring the Solomons campaign to a quick and successful end. The target is once again the enemy carrier fleet, which is now reduced to only a couple of operational carriers, thanks to the feats achieved by our submarine crews against USS Wasp and USS Saratoga. Carrier Division 5 will search for the enemy TG(s) and sink the American carriers, in order to clear the Guadalcanal area from any Navy aircraft activity. In the meantime, surface units will silence Henderson Fleet with heavy naval guns and clean the sea-road that leads to Lunga Point, where our troops should disembark in a handful of days. Once our Tassafaronga position will be reinforced enough, we will launch a decisive offensive against the Marines at Henderson Field, and push them back for good to Aola bay, into the angry sea.>
<SantaCruzVictoryDb>(*JA) <Pilots and sailors of the Imperial Fleet, we're proud of your decisive action! By annihilating the enemy fleet, you showed our devil enemies the valorous might of the Kido Butai. Now that the enemy carriers are meeting with the deep sound of the ocean, thanks to large effort to resupply them, our land forces in Guadalcanal are preparing for a last offensive which will sweep off the remaining forsaken Marines forces. Good work!>
<SantaCruzDefeatDb>(*JA) <Due to our failure here, our situation in Guadalcanal is definitely put into jeopardy. All we can do now is to hope that Admiral Abe will defeat the enemy surfaces forces at sea - a goal that will get even harder to reach, as the enemy forces are still strongly supported by the enemy naval air groups we didn't manage to put out of action today.>
<SantaCruzDb>(*JA) <The enemy suffered very heavy losses, but this effort cost us many friends both in the air and on the sea. The enemy ships were defended by a new type of high-rate AA weapon that proved to be devastating against our defenceless attack aircrafts. Nevertheless, the courage of our crews turned this encounter into a great victory that avenges our drawback in Midway. Now that the Kido Butai did its job, it is up to Admiral Abe and its surface forces to give the US Navy its last blow in the waters of Guadalcanal.>

<Marianas1Br>(nJA)	<We had planned that the enemy would first assault Palau - we missed the point. US ships will soon be facing the Marianas - fortunately enough, we were ready in this case too. Admiral Toyoda's plan relies heavily on the ability of our land-based fighters to hamper the enemy efforts in the first days of the battle. Then, admiral Ozawa's ships will come to finish off any further enemy naval resistance. It is a good plan that has good chances to succeed if everyone, both in the Army and in the Navy, executes properly its assigned duty.>
<Marianas1Br>(aJA)	<We had planned that the enemy would first assault Palau - we missed the point. US ships will soon be facing the Marianas - fortunately enough, we were ready in this case too. Numerous Army air units are stationed on Guam, Saipan and Tinian, waiting for the western devils to show up. Once the enemy aircrafts will have be found, attack them without a single minute of rest, and ease the task of the Combined Fleet, the ships and the aircrews of which will finish off the enemy task groups. We believe there is a chance to turn this engagement into a new "destruction" battle at our own advantage: we are counting on you!>
<Marianas1VictoryDb>(*JA)	<Congratulations Samourai! The Kido Butai's action was terribly efficient, and the western devils will not forget the harsh lesson they just learnt here against our courageous soldiers. Many enemy ships were sunk, and the Marianas invasion was postponed; admirals Toyoda, Ozawa, Kurita and Nagumo will soon design together a new offensive plan in order to re-take the initiative in the Central Pacific area. The victory may not seem so far away, finally!>
<Marianas1DefeatDb>(*JA)	<I heard about officers that committed seppuku for much less important dishonour than ours. The Marianas engagement, instead of being a great victory, was a crushing disaster! The Kido Butai may never recover from the defeat it just suffered here, against surprisingly competent enemy carrier forces. Let's regroup our last forces for a ultimate desperate effort…>
<Marianas1Db>(*JA)		<We failed at inflicting the enemy important losses, and we lost the remaining bulk of our embarked air assets. This is a dark day for the Kido Butai, even if the naval losses are not so catastrophic after all. Anyway, we have think about our future operations: the Imperial Fleet still has a chance to oppose decisively and violently the American advance the moments our evil enemies will try to attack the Philippines. But defeats are not an option anymore if we want to keep our victory chances alive.>
<Marianas1Br>(*US)		<The Mariana Islands are our next destination. Operation Forager's goal is the complete invasion of the three main islands of the archipelago, providing us a forward base for both our naval forces and our strategic bomber units. Like in the previous offensives of the same kind, you are to heavily sweep the enemy airbases of the area, and then provide close air support to our landing forces. But remember we are not assaulting atolls anymore - our targets here are real islands, with real fortifications and real defences. We are also hoping for the Mobile Fleet to make an attempt to battle us around the objective: be prepared for heavy CAP and search activities, as long as we will have not found the enemy main body. If there is to be an encounter, it must be a decisive one: the Marianas shall be a doom to the Mobile Fleet.>
<Marianas1VictoryDb>(*US)	<Good job, kids, Guam, Saipan and Tinian were secured with much fewer losses than planned. The Combined Fleet tried to seek a decisive battle - and indeed, it succeed, but not in the expected way for the Japanese. Imperial navy's losses were heavy and, more than that, they are irreplaceable. The embarked aircrews suffered much from the battle too - thousand of Japanese airmen died during these few days of fighting. We gave the Imperial Navy a final blow it will never recover from.>
<Marianas1DefeatDb>(*US)	<Underestimating the enemy is a bloody mistake - and the whole operation Forager WAS a mistake. We suffered heavy losses both on the ground and on the sea, facing an unexpected enemy air and naval resistance. We had to get back eastward, leaving the islands under Japanese rule. The Mobile Fleet showed that it had not lost its professionalism despite previous defeats and losses. What a painful disillusion!>
<Marianas1Db>(*US)		<Guam, Saipan and Tinian are now secured. If the ground battle proceeded nearly normally - despite heavier losses than planned - the sea battle was something like an unfinished business. Despite the submarines' victories and our airmen's attacks, the enemy main body escaped only partly damaged, and Admiral Spruance did not obtain the crushing victory he was looking for. Alas, we will have to wait some additional weeks before a new opportunity of this kind. Good job anyway - the "Great Marianas Turkeys Shot" showed that enemy embarked aircrews are not a real danger anymore>

