<SingaporeBr>(nJA)	<Soldiers of the Imperial Navy, your hour of glory has come ! All the Navy air crews stationed in Indochina are committed to our offensive operations against the Malayan peninsula and the evil and despotic British troops. The bomber crews will have to harass the enemy shipping and to strike the British airbases and depots. The fighter crews will provide an efficient cover over the target areas, against the RAF Buffaloes and Hurricanes - the experience and the superb airmanship of our veteran pilots will certainly make the difference. Get to your planes, and long live the Empire !>
<SingaporeVictoryDb>(nJA)	<We couldn't imagine it would be so easy. General Yamashita lead his forces with great skill, capturing the Singapore fortress with inferior forces. The Army airmen did a great job at neutralizing the British far-eastern fleet and the RAF detachments of the area. The whitemen's ruling in the area is now complete history, thanks to you and your comrades ! Now we still have to enter Burma and India - then, we will have all the needed time to rest in Calcutta.>
<SingaporeDefeatDb>(nJA)	<The operation didn't proceed very well, and general Yamashita failed to exploit the surprise advantage. The British were waiting for us, both in the air, on the sea, and on the ground. We didn't manage to silence the enemy fleet, which did our own navy great harm, and we failed at contesting the RAF its air supremacy over Malaya. The General Staff in Tokyo is very disappointed by our "performance", and has to make some new plans to take this setback into account.>
<SingaporeDb>(nJA)		<The operation was a hard one, but we finally succeeded at driving the British presence out of the Malayan peninsula. Losses were consequent, but the objective was worth our sacrifices. The Singapore fortress is history, and our forces can now head towards Burma and Dutch East Indies to finish off our job in Southern Asia.> <SingaporeBr>(aUK)		<Several hours ago, Japan declared war upon the United States, striking the anchored Pacific Fleet at Pearl Harbour. It is both a good and a bad news: what is good is that now, we can count on the United States' help in our struggle against the Axis forces; what is worse is the fact that there are great chances that Malaya may get assaulted by Japanese amphibious forces in the forthcoming days. We must get ready for any eventuality. This evening, the Royal Navy will sail out from Singapore and look for enemy troopships. The RAF is to provide cover to our boats and to Singapore city, which will certainly have to face air raids in a very near future. The success or the defeat in Malaya relies much on the RAF crews' shoulders: do not disappoint us and destroy the aggressor, or Singapore may have to fight for its survival.>

<SingaporeBr>(*U*) <Three weeks ago Japan declared war upon the United States, striking the anchored Pacific Fleet at Pearl Harbour. It is both good and bad news: what is good is that now we can count on the United States' help in our struggle against the Axis forces; what is worse is the fact Japanese forces have already landed in Malaya. We must get ready for any eventuality. This evening, the Royal Navy will sail out from Singapore and look for enemy troopships. The RAF is to provide cover for our vessels and for Singapore city, which will certainly have to face air raids in a very near future. Our success or defeat in Malaya relies very much on the RAF: do not disappoint us and destroy the aggressor, or Singapore itself may have to fight for its very survival.>
//<SingaporeBr>(*U*)		<Several hours ago, Japan declared war upon the United States, striking the anchored Pacific Fleet at Pearl Harbour. It is both a good and a bad news: what is good is that now, we can count on the United States' help in our struggle against the Axis forces; what is worse is the fact that there are great chances that Malaya may get assaulted by Japanese amphibious forces in the forthcoming days. We must get ready for any eventuality. This evening, the Royal Navy will sail out from Singapore and look for enemy troopships. The RAF is to provide cover to our boats and to Singapore city, which will certainly have to face air raids in a very near future. The success or the defeat in Malaya relies much on the RAF crews' shoulders: do not disappoint us and destroy the aggressor, or Singapore may have to fight for its survival.>
<SingaporeVictoryDb>(*U*)	<Congratulations gentlemen ! The Japanese octopus was stopped here, on the doorstep of Malaya. Yamashita forces were halted and had to dig-in in order to resist our counter-attacks. The Imperial army suffered its first defeat, and it is greatly thanks to you and your comrades. Now that Singapore is safe, we have to think about sending the Japanese back to their home for good...>
<SingaporeDefeatDb>(*U*)	<We couldn't resist the Japanese overwhelming advance. Our naval and air losses prevented us to protect the Malaysian coast from the enemy landings, and Yamashita, who is already called the "Tiger of Malaya", easily captured the whole peninsula and even our so-called "fortress" of Singapore. This is a disaster ! Thousand of Commonwealth troops had to surrender without firing a single shot. Will the British presence in the Far-East will ever recover from such a bitter failure.>
<SingaporeDb>(*U*)		<We did what we could, but Malaya and Singapore finally fell after a handful of weeks made of fierce fighting and bloody assaults. Thanks to our efficient command, British troops were not routed and retreated in good order towards Burma. We will have to fight our real battle for the saving of the Far-Eastern British Empire there !>

