<NewGuineaBr>(*JA)			<By building up a solid airbase in Lae and Salamaua, we managed to obtain a very serious stepping stone in our effort to conquer the remaining uncontrolled areas of southern New-Guinea. The capture of Buna was the logical consequence of our advance in the area. Our next objective is the allied strongpoint of Port Moresby, which has to be taken at all costs, either by land or by sea. Port Moresby must fall, hammered by the combined efforts of the Imperial Army and the Imperial Navy, as if the enemy base was between the devil and the deep blue sea. Port Moresby captured, there will be nothing left to oppose our victorious armies on their way to Australia.>
<NewGuineaVictoryDb>(*JA)	<The way to Port Moresby is now cleared from any enemy ground opposition. US and ANZAC troops were not a match for our superior samourai foot-soldiers, long-used to fierce jungle fighting. The hostile environment played on our side, and contributed to weaken the enemy defence lines, which didn't resist our overwhelming advance despite a stiff resistance. Well done soldier, the Imperial forces are now about to land in Australia and to eventually end our struggle for Southern Pacific for good.>	
<NewGuineaDefeatDb>(*JA)	<Allied troops proved to be much more efficient at jungle fighting than expected. They did adapt to this new kind of warfare very quickly, and countered all our initiatives without leaving us a single chance to react and strike back. This battle was a stalemate from the start - there was no room for an Imperial victory, and we are glad that we finally managed to pull out from this upcoming disaster, in order to re-deploy our troops elsewhere in the Pacific, in a location they will be much more valuable and useful, instead of being wasted in this gigantic quagmire with no hope of success.>
<NewGuineaDb>(*JA)			<Despite our efforts in the area, Owen Range heights and Milne Bay remained in Allied hands. We failed at fulfilling our objectives, but the heavy losses inflicted to the US and ANZAC troops delayed much the re-conquest of the island, and the Allied Headquarters' plans and coordination are jeopardized for a time in the southern New-Guinea sector. In fact, even if the jungle warfare is currently not at our advantage anymore, we will soon leave the south-eastern coast of New-Guinea with the feeling of having done something there, even if it wasn't the positive result we expected…>
<NewGuineaBr>(*U*)			<The West end of the New Guinea island, is the main hotspot of our campaign in the sector. It is both a land and sea struggle: we will have to support our US, Australian and New-Zealander foot troops advancing through hazardous swamps and exhausting heights, while disrupting mercilessly the incoming enemy troop convoys that would try to land behind our lines, threatening our Port Moresby main base, despite the protection provided by the Owen Range mountains natural barrier. We have to push back the enemy forces, and capture the Buna airfields, as a first step before freeing Salamaua and Lae from the Japanese occupation.>
<NewGuineaVictoryDb>(*U*)	<New Guinea was a deadly battlefield, nearly as deadly as the Japanese themselves. But we did it, and Japanese forces are now pushed back for good. Now that we are sure that our enemy will not trample the southern New-Guinean ground anymore, we may think about pushing further North. Lae, New Britain and the Northern Coast are still waiting for us soldiers, let's finish off our job! >
<NewGuineaDefeatDb>(*U*)	<The jungle of New Guinea was the most deadly place on Earth. We lost as many soldiers to enemy fire as to the unhealthy and dangerous natural environment, which literally smothered our efforts and exhausted our weak fighting forces. Now we have to retreat to the southern coast, being unable to delay furthermore the Japanese advance. Let's hope that our failure will not seriously endanger Australia's safety, or we may regret our dear lost jungle once we will be under the Mikado's rule…>
<NewGuineaDb>(*U*)			<Finally the Japanese were driven away from Southern New Guinea - but it did cost thousand US, Aussie and Kiwi lives, while the only true stake here was a neverending unhealthy surface of deep jungle… Were all these trees and marshes worth our soldiers' sacrifice? If you take into account that it did indeed save Australia from the Japanese octopus, I would be disposed to answer "yes, it did". Good job!>

